DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(87)90023-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438788790023X
AB  - The Mexican Revolution, like in so many cases of war, witnessed a large inflationary process which appeared in early 1913. The group in power, and other revolutionary factions, resorted to seizing bank reserves and to printing money. The exchange rate these various monies depreciated steadily until mid-1916. The new government tried to stabilize prices and the exchange rate by having a low level of reserves, but the effort failed. shortly after, the government repudiated its own money by demanding that a growing amount of the various taxes to be paid in hard currency; at the same time, some sectors of the ecnomy also demanded their salaries to be paid in gold money. Finally, as if by magic, gold and silver coins returned to circulation reversing Gresham's Law and the gold standard was reassumed, thus stabilizing the exchange rate and level of prices. Some of these results are also compared with those experienced by various countries in similar situations.
ER  - 

