UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387887900071
AB  - The paper develops models of speculative runs and collapse of fixed exchange rate regimes which result from credit policies that are ultimately inconsistent with a fixed exchange rate. While no substantially new results are offered, the formulation itself is of interest in highlighting the important ideas that have emerged in this area. We modify the Flood-Garber model to make the analysis more comparable with the deterministic case. Specifically we assume that the money growth process is specified in terms of growth rates rather than absolute increments and as a uniform rather than exponential distribution. The modified analysis lends itself to a simple geometric interpretation of the Krugman and Flood-Garber models, highlighting the important difference between the deterministic and stochastic models. In the former the speculative attack run is concentrated, in the latter the transition to floating is diffuse. Reserve losses exceed increases in domestic credit because of a rising probability of transition,and reserve depletion accelerates on the way to the regime change.
ER  - 

