AB  - This paper reports on an attempt to quantify the relative contribution of global conditions and domestic policies to the origins of individual countries' debt difficulties. The need for systematic quantification is beyond doubt, but there is no satisfactory methodology for estimation on a comparable basis across countries. This paper provides some preliminary results and highlights some of the methodological difficulties that must be confronted in such an effort. The results, for 19 countries, must be interpreted with care, but nonetheless underscore the significant differences among developing countries in the origins of, and response to, debt difficulties. Recognition of this diversity is important for understanding the present positions of many developing countries, and assessing the needed shifts in policy if there is to be an acceptable resolution to the difficulties.
