AB  - The McKinnon model of repressed capital and money markets is tested against concise accounts of the development of such markets in England, France, Germany and Italy. Differences of a national and institutional character are observed. It is concluded that the question is more complex than one of repressed vs. unrepressed capital markets, and that the explosive reactions in Latin America from recent deregulation may have originated not in inconsistencies in policies, wrong order of reform steps, or other current explanations so much as precipitousness which failed to give markets sufficient time to settle down between deregulation measures, getting asset prices right (rather than underpriced and overtraded) and permitting expectations time to settle in stable fashion.
